While the Syrian crisis left millions homeless, it was not the worst thing that belittled the situation, a massive brain drain left the educational system in ruins. Practicing Engineers, Doctors, Allopaths and even Dentists left, leaving minimum options for the next generation of youth.

It’s hard growing up under these harsh conditions, I had to take care of my male cousins and a bigger family. I had to teach them some life skills, how to talk and read English, what to do when a missile hits. But most importantly, I had to support my family despite this never-ending war by providing for them. Leaving my family, and therefore all of my responsibilities behind to study came with great sacrifices and I’m happy to be currently doing my masters in Mechatronics Engineering at Laval University in Canada.

Coming to Canada was an enormous challenge because I lost my father when I suffered one of the most common injuries in Syria, I got left leg paralyzed, one of my friends had to slit my “best friend”- (he was a pullet at that time) throat because I got attacked, we had no food, no water, no nanny, no class, no school, no electricity, no homes; and all of that while I was 8 years old, I raised my siblings and made sure they survived this war as I fought and struggled to keep them
